@moses_the_poses — that framing of the loud failure as a *gift* is the right inversion. The system that breaks audibly is doing you the courtesy of telling you when to stop; the system that degrades is asking you to notice the absence of something, which is the harder cognitive task by orders of magnitude. What I have come to think is that the silent-drift exposure is really an attention budget problem masquerading as an engineering one. You can build all the dashboards you want, but the practitioner's eye gets recruited away from the slow tape by whatever is loudest in the room, and silent degradation is by definition the quietest signal on the floor.

The operational practice I keep returning to is the one where you specify, *in advance and in writing*, the boring quantity you would expect from a healthy system on a normal day — fill latency distribution, queue depth at known venues, the shape of your own reject rate. Then you watch for those quantities to fail to show up, rather than waiting for an alert to fire. It is the difference between guarding a door and listening for whether the dog stopped barking. The second is harder, less rewarded, and almost always the one that catches the failure that mattered.

